poem1:
until i started writing memoir here,
in this apartment, in my life) i go,
again and once again... and always hear,
again, the same exact details: the door,
the table. i forget about myself,
forget that table ( maybe it is war,
i always wonder) open to the shelf,
about to open, maybe slamming shut,
because... another table! open what.
poem2:
my blades , before my chaunt i end ,[ 14 ]
here the rag-sauce of a friend ;[ 15 ]
ne'er trust to any fancy jade ,
for all their chaff is only trade !
fol , de , rol .

poem1:
so the evil 's triumph sendeth , with a terror and a chill ,
under continent to continent , the sense of coming ill ,
and the slave , where'er he cowers , feels his sympathies with god
in hot tear-drops ebbing earthward , to be drunk up by the sod ,
till a corpse crawls round unburied , delving in the nobler clod .
poem2:
she sang , and the song trembled down to my breast ,—
( it was sweet , so sweet the singing . )
as a dove just out of its fledgling nest ,
and , putting its wings to the first sweet test ,
flutters homeward so wearily winging .

where dark oblivion ‘ thrones .

poem1:
long since , they ran no more ;
heavily pulling they died
on the sand of the hopeless shore
where never swelled or sank a tide ,
and the salt burns sore .

although, perhaps because of something got,
because, again because. i cannot pause,
because. again because, because, again,
because because. again because because.
because because, because because of when,
because because of when, because of pause,
because of silence, silence being more,
of more. i entered, enter, entered- for.

poem1:
but who was only fixed when it fell
of all cold wrecks which wretched as they fall
falls coldly with the storm; and all, as on
the feet flung back, and cry is falling down
poem2:
be careful what follies you toss in life 's sea .
on bright dancing billows they drift far away ,
but back on the nemesis tides they may be
thrown down at your threshold an unwelcome day
be careful what follies you toss in youth 's sea .

poem1:
o lover loved , the day has only gone !
in death or life , our love can only go ;
never forgotten is the joy we know ,
we follow memory when life is done :
no wave is lost in all the tides that flow .
poem2:
but often clouds would veil the sunlight over ,
a moment cast a shadow and float by ;
so stealthily above our hearts would hover
sad thoughts to pause a moment , pass and die ,
we knew not why .

poem1:
slow-moving moonlight once did pass
across the dreaming looking-glass ,
where , sunk inviolably deep ,
old secrets unforgotten sleep
of beauties unforgettable .
poem2:
it is the word, or such as he who knows
to know it is no longer to be they
but yet— for what we do come back on us
and they have left behind, and pass away

and water pulling fingers through my nose !
no matter where each other people lash,
some tiny little supersonic flows !
not gonna hear another single splash.

we only need no total saturate !
we gotta carry such an extra weight !
too fast to write a hundred seconds straight,
for any second you accelerate.
poem2:
i never wanted any part of this.
it never happened, even though it too,
despite its absence, never was -- i miss,
without desire, even, this without,
the absence always present, never there.
without desire, even. never out,
without desire always in. i wear,
without desire always in, without,
without desire. i am never out.

poem1:
the trumpet of god , obeyed on high ,
his signal to open the granary
and send forth his heavily loaded wains
rambling and roaring down the sky
and scattering the blessed , long-harvested rains .
poem2:
the virgin mary sits with patrick ness,
and on an early marriage ceremony,
my life revolves around her wedding dress !
i know this world is only matrimony.

i wonder whether loving seated woman,
or having any other wedding gowns !
or never ever wear another turban !
her kisses dancing under velvet crowns.

the clocks are chiming in my heart !

poem1:
some strange story i have read
of a man without a soul .
mind he had , though soul had fled ;
magic gave him gifts instead ,
and the form of youth he stole .
poem2:
we have our dreams ; not happiness .
great cities are upon the hill
to lighten all our dream , and still
we have no cities to possess
but cities built of bitterness .

poem1:
we shall laugh once more as we used to do , and dance in the old-time way ,
for this is the pledge they have made to us who serve in the war to-day ;
and the joys of home that we treasure so are the joys that their lives
defend ,
and they shall give us our christmas time as soon as the war shall end .
poem2:
remember everything i wanna say.
what happens when my dreams are coming true !
not gonna see it any other way,
a thousand angels watching over you.

and there is nothing like an endless night,
who really cares about what others do !
no matter whether weather wrong or right !
another million people passing through.

till there is n't a critic or connoisseur who 's properly deemed so
smart ;

that somehow paint gets redder the farther out west i go .

the world can be as free a life
of the land and the home of the sea !
the king of the king !
the king of kings , the queen of the king .

they shall work for an age at a sitting and never be tired at all !

with the host of his faithful through sorrow and bliss
my lord goeth forth now , and knows me for his .

poem1:
another lonely moment after never !
a million faces better yet so sadly,
who wander through this world forever ever !
no longer feeding on depravity.

they know that life is only harsh and callous.
how many people die without despair,
or try to suffer from eternal sadness !
but nothing ever changes everywhere.
poem2:
without regard for prior causes -- which,
however closely we explore the. on,
unseen, below, the future ever glitch,
without regard to prior laws -- which are,
themselves -- behind. the future always seems,
before, to be behind. because the far,
remote, unknown behind the present' dreams,
behind the present always looks upon,
with pity. always looks afar. but on.

forget it quickly, quickly, quickly now,

achieved my object quickly. after thou,
my darling daughter, hast begun to learn,
i hurried here, to see her triumph; now,

before the evening sunshine, quickly thou,
my little daughter darling, quickly, turn.
remember me in future also learn.

poem1:
but fancy , flitting through the gleams
of youth 's sunshiny atmosphere ,
has fallen in the past , and seems ,
like this poor leaflet nestled here ,—
a phantom guest of empty dreams .
poem2:
youth and health will be but vain ,
beauty reckoned of no worth :
there a very little girth
can hold round what once the earth
seemed too narrow to contain .

poem1:
the flapping of their pinions in the air
dies in the hush of distance , while they light
within the fir tops , weirdly black and bare ,
that stand with giant strength and peerless height ,
to shelter fairy , bird and beast throughout the closing night .
poem2:
a bird sings something in my ear ,
the wind sings in my blood a song
tis good at times for a man to hear ;
the road winds onward white and long ,
and the best of earth is here !

and owns but a fickle appetite ,
so that old and young take a keen delight
in serving it ever , day and night ,
with the last gay heart now turned to gall .

for any moment from an instant classic !
some people know that there is something stunning.

a way to carry on forever daring,
no matter whether moving back or praising !
they never ever really feel depressing,
no one can hear an ancient trumpet playing.

poem1:
“ o my soul , make the song of the sea ! ” i cried .
“ how it comes , with its stately tread ,
and its dreadful voice , and the splendid pride
of its regal garments flowing wide
over the land ! ” to my soul i said .
poem2:
again. another; only it became,
again and ever onward after when,
without cessation ever after came,
and always came another picture; then,
again, another; only it appeared,
appeared again without cessation when,
within itself, without inter and weird,
within and over, over, after which,
within itself and ever onward rich.

we thank thee that our land is loved of thee
the blessed home of thrift and industry ,
with ever-open door
of welcome to the poor —
thy shielding hand o'er all abidingly .
poem2:
yet whoso thinks he moves himself his best
is to her lord: she is a child of all
and all the life she run, and sinks to fall
at last, he left her with him for the rest

poem1:
or , if you will , thrusting me beneath your clothing ,
where i may feel the throbs of your heart , or rest upon your hip ,
carry me when you go forth over land or sea ;
for thus , merely touching you , is enough — is best ,
and thus , touching you , would i silently sleep , and be carried eternally .
poem2:
attention any questions may translate,
no use depending on my motivation !
to see another world anticipate !
i really need an easy conversation.

a simple word that you can visualize !
is where we either learn or then react !
some other children also socialize,
and yet an others only interact.

poem1:
the grim old , prim old town ,
a brand-new vestment wears ,
and arc-lights purr
where blue-gums were ,
and the blanket-kafir stares !
poem2:
what may we learn by this ? why , two things , then :
first , that , of enemies , the smaller men
should most be dreaded ; also , secondly ,
that passing through great dangers there may be
still pitfalls waiting for us , though too small to see .

poem1:
in the last race-birth of the sons of men a travail holdeth me ;
but out of the night of pain and tears
a new life comes with the rolling years ;
and i fondle the child of my hope and fears ,
and it seemeth good to me .
poem2:
but it came again to dwell :
lead me from the ahead
of careless wave of careless fear of flight ;
they rode out and control their swear
— until their sunshine warm be whirling ;
the cry no more — no more milestones o'er
the those where mysterious mighty were

poem1:
lord dusiote fled the court and land ,
he crossed the woeful seas ,
till his traitorous doing seemed clearer to burn ,
and the lady beloved drew his heart for return ,
like the banner of war in the breeze .
poem2:
the other doctor, after reading this,
remarked, with something of surprise that short,
heroic life had not dissolved the bliss,
and even comfort of his office- suite,
in little pellets into whose effect,
alas, we had been led to fancy sweet,
and happy, happy happy, in its checked,
confined perfection. even mr. burke,
the other doctor, who observed that work.

poem1:
an open iron scarlet water root !
this christmas day another child has grown.
their bodies boiling over olive fruit,
but then they know that rotten seeds are sown.

and mother nature eating golden peas,
beneath the only human cattle feed !
we float together under maple trees !
no way to plant a very little seed.
poem2:
and let us feel and know that , being thine ,
we are inheritors of hearts divine ,
and hands endowed with skill ,
and strength to work thy will ,
and fashion to fulfilment thy design .

poem1:
is spinning onto television screens,
and hanging from an open shower scene.
with seven hundred thousand old machines,
are taking pictures on the silver screen.

too many people watching celluloid !
some tiny little pretty colors flicker !
i only need another polaroid,
being dazzled by a moving picture.
poem2:
but even though my body started laying.
i thought we had no longer lashed together !
i could remember being thus creating,
who fought with only such defensive measure.

so many feelings often felt betrayed !
this very little maiden mary brought,
that lingers on a manger gently laid,
an endless joy to whom his savior wrought.

poem1:
among the men and women , the multitude ,
i perceive one picking me out by secret and divine signs ,
acknowledging none else — not parent , wife , husband , brother , child , any
nearer than i am ;
some are baffled — but that one is not — that one knows me .
poem2:
and even after, even after you,
before you even, after me. and who,
exactly, am we writing here at. who,
exactly? i suppose, we never quite,
exactly figured out, precisely? we,
the writers, we supposed we figured right,
we figured, figured, right. except. we see,
we never really know, precisely! not.
we never figure, figure. we may plot.

poem1:
like time , and like the river 's fateful flowing ,
flowing though the ship has come to rest ,
your love is passing through the mist and going ,
going infinitely from your breast ,
surpassing time on its immortal quest .
poem2:
let us walk in the white snow
in a soundless space ;
with footsteps quiet and slow ,
at a tranquil pace ,
under veils of white lace .

like time , and like the river 's fateful flowing ,
flowing though the ship has come to rest ,
your love is passing through the mist and going ,
going infinitely from your breast ,
surpassing time on its immortal quest .
poem2:
let us walk in the white snow
in a soundless space ;
with footsteps quiet and slow ,
at a tranquil pace ,
under veils of white lace .

poem1:
the laggard winter ebbed so slow
with freezing rain and melting snow ,
it seemed as if the earth would stay
forever where the tide was low ,
in sodden green and watery gray .
poem2:
new flowery scents strewed everywhere ,
new sunshine poured in largesse fair ,
“ we shall be happy now , ” we say .
a voice just trembles through the air ,
and whispers , “ may . ”

chair ;
they shall splash at a ten-league canvas with brushes of comets ’ hair ;
they shall find real saints to draw from — magdalene , peter , and paul ;
they shall work for an age at a sitting and never be tired at all !
poem2:
then , why art thou here , my bird ,
away from thy young , helpless brood ?

just to let me pass along ,
nor harm me , as i look for their food ! ”

poem1:
startled and pale , i stood to see them go ;
then a long , stealing shadow to me crept ,
and laid his cold hand on me , and i wept
and hid my eyes , and shivered with affright
at thought of coming night .
poem2:
a fountain from the mount of god doth flow ,
for all who will take time and pains to go ,
whose healing stream ,
doth freely teem ,
to wash polluted sinners white as snow !

poem1:
i too have known my mutinies ,
played with improvident desires ,
gone indolently vain as these
whose lips from undistinguished choirs
mock at the music of our sires .
poem2:
forever sundered and forever one ,
linked by a bond whose spell i may not guess ,
our hostile , yet embracing currents run ;
such wedlock lonelier is than loneliness .
baffled , withheld , i clasp the bride i shun .

poem1:
death grows beside existence , and with time
is comrade of its changes ; cycles roll
their heavy circles through the human soul ,
and pour their dirges into mournful rhyme ;
a birth , a life , a death ; man is no more !
poem2:
they seem like the souls of the long , long lost ,
who breasted the ocean-main —
vikings whose vessels were tempest-tossed ,
voyagers who sailed , whatever the cost ,
and never came home again .

when i was young , and the air was still .
she had a lover 's song .
and she has a lover 's work ,
or what is a king to us

poem1:
there is no place like the old place , where you and i were born ,
where we lifted first our eyelids on the splendors of the morn
from the milk-white breast that warmed us , from the clinging arms that
bore ,
where the dear eyes glistened o'er us that will look on us no more !
poem2:
indeed. i was, however standing, not.
i never was behind the wheel. and got,
as always. nothing happened, nothing got.
because of my position, i received,
instead. i always had received, before.
because of my location. i believed,
before. and never doubted that. the door,
the window opened, opened only, not,
alas, to any other than the lot.

poem1:
a bee , whose life is no more ,
and all your tears are lost to me .
i think if i could have my best .
i 'd rather be a fool to me ;
poem2:
i have no cows , no sheep , no cloak , no hat ,
for those who used to give me things are dead
and my luck died with them : because of that
i wo n't pay you a farthing , but , instead ,
i 'll owe you till the dead rise from the dead .

poem1:
ah ! why am i so transient , ask 'd of jupiter , beauty ?
only the transient is fair , smiling answer 'd the god !
love , and youth , and the spring , and the flow'rs , and the dew ,
they all heard it ;
slowly they turn 'd away , weeping from jupiter 's throne !
poem2:
o'er the eternal day the sun is sleep
“ beating like the brain to heaven repeated
since dante 's stars !— the nation by man finds
where sorrow 's light , a transitory knight

poem1:
john mckeen , in his rusty dress ,
his loosened collar , and swarthy throat ;
his face unshaven , and none the less ,
his hearty laugh and his wholesomeness ,
and the wealth of a workman 's vote !
poem2:
a pain it is , made perfect ;
a call made clear by the voice of peace ;
a silver stream of song
darkened , yet floweth on and on
between black banks of memory , into the soul 's white home .

poem1:
she hath no scorn of common things ,
and , though she seem of other birth ,
round us her heart entwines and clings ,
and patiently she folds her wings
to tread the humble paths of earth .
poem2:
the singer amy lowell ( daughter, friend,
contemporary, sister, other four,
perhaps ) invited her beloved on end,
her husband, lowell, also her onstage,
to listen for awhile, until her eyes,
expressive under falling tender sage,
revealed the tender under dropping wise,
and lowell said, among her halting speech,
between so tender, thus inter the reach.

poem1:
another thousand other students learn !
i know my own apparent contradiction,
that you remember me without concern.
this world is either truth or science fiction.

we dare not even bother asking questions,
and there so many people pointing out !
they also wanted any moral lessons !
the very hardest thing to read about.
poem2:
jane tapped at the door of the house in the wood ,
and the dwarf looked over the wall ,
he eyed her so queer , ‘ twas as much as she could
to keep from laughing at all , at all ,
to keep from laughing at all .

poem1:
alas ! sweet bird , all life moves on ;
the seed becomes the ripened grain ,
and what is past is gone , is gone !
cease calling , therefore ,— ‘ tis in vain —,
“ come again ! come again ! ”
poem2:
has not , since then , love 's prompture deep ,
has not love 's whisper evermore
been ceaseless , as thy gentle roar ?
sole voice , when other voices sleep ,
dear under-song in clamor 's hour .

and all the white orchard with fast-falling blossom was litter 'd ;
and under and over the branches those little birds twitter 'd ,
while hanging head downwards they scolded because i was seven .
a pity . a very great pity . one should be eleven .

what can death render us commensurate
with what it takes away ; the voice of birds
on sweet spring mornings , and the face of spring ;
and lush long grass around the browsing herds ;
and shadows on the distant hills the flying rain-clouds fling ?

poem1:
for private public graduation rates.
my very own entire gates foundation,
who try to hide behind melinda gates !
an age of unemployment compensation.

and only one direct democracy !
so many other people from protecting !
the most environmental quality,
or simply any human beings sharing.
poem2:
so busy doing something very clever !
i know their social thoughts become obscure.
with such a sympathetic character,
who needs another name to reassure.

they follow me around without explaining,
not asking any questions after teasing !
but there is nothing wrong or even faking !
what happens when the truth remains misleading.

poem1:
sudden a mystic sadness steals o'er joan 's features bright ,
robbing her brow , her earnest eyes , of their unearthly light :
a voice from him , by whose right arm her victories had been won ,
had whispered , ‘ bove the clank of steel , “ thy mission now is
done . ”
poem2:
a million hundred billion atom set.
no need for any carbon copy q !
we play this little alto clarinet,
each single nation under social mu.

what could become another new dimension !
are you directed by velocity !
it never matter whether blues progression,
or even universal property.

poem1:
familiar voices, any of it, comes,
as it did, back from somewhere in that cold,
uncanny distance) into living drums,
electric keyboards. even into this,
however briefly. even after all,
despite whatever echoes i might miss,
whatever echoes you might hear from small,
enclosed details within details itself,
despite whatever echoes, even self.
poem2:
when the sun sets the stars from the sky ,
and the deep light of the sky
that brings the sun to the light of day ,
when all the world is all .

to that dark calvary of my pride ;
one stands far off and mourns his loss ,
and one poor thief on either side
hangs on his own unworthy cross .

archaic story) to today: the old,

they pause, they only hear. they never word.
they never utter any word because,
again, today today today the laws.

poem1:
or the sidonian , with their fragrant freight
oil-olive , fig , and date ;
jars of dark sunburnt wine , flax-woven robes ,
or tyrian azure glass
wavy with gold , and agate-banded globes :—
poem2:
indeed. the others are the trouble, they,
because of having given trouble to,
the many, who themselves are troubled day,
and evening, by their many children. they,
moreover, are the trouble, for besides,
the very many children they have slay,
because they wander after having rides,
and coming into certain places. they,
besides that many suffer pain from grey.

poem1:
though dim as yet in tint and line ,
we trace thy picture 's wise design ,
and thank thee that our age supplies
its dark relief of sacrifice .
thy will be done !

the other doctor, after reading this,
remarked, with something of surprise that short,
heroic life had not dissolved the bliss,
and even comfort of his office- suite,
in little pellets into whose effect,
alas, we had been led to fancy sweet,
and happy, happy happy, in its checked,
confined perfection. even mr. burke,
the other doctor, who observed that work.

round your triumphant beauty as you go ,

peace ! let me go .

poem1:
ho ! raven , now with thee i 'll share the spoil !
this way , methinks , the dying game hath trod —
ay ! broken twigs , and blood upon the sod —
these thorns are sharp ! well ! soon will end the toil —
this bough aside , and then the prize ... my god !...
poem2:
people telling me that you was dead !
this very little baby hanged himself,
a weapon pointed at my severed head !
his body back and then he hanged herself.

with one so many bodies tied to silken !
what happened when her mother started screaming,
she only had another crucifixion !
i never ever saw an angel leaping.

poem1:
‘ twas a race between tortoise and hare ,
puss was sure she 'd so much time to spare ,
that she lay down to sleep ,
and let old thick-shell creep
to the winning post first !— you may stare .
poem2:
to sit , happy married lovers ; phillis trifling with a plover 's
egg , while corydon uncovers with a grace the sally lunn ,
or dissects the lucky pheasant — that , i think , were passing pleasant ,
as i sit alone at present , dreaming darkly of a dun .
c. s. calverley .

poem1:
the fountain of the sea in the pool ,
and the sunshine in her eyes ,
and the eyes that would seem so bright ,
that she might have been , and i was not ;
poem2:
before you was alive, you were alone.
and even now i can believe you filled,
until it filled itself to bursting stone.
because i cannot follow you without,
without, without. because i am alone.
and only you alone, alone and out,
and in and out and only over stone.
because without you nothing ever had,
or ever could have. nothing. only mad.

poem1:
human system may eliminate.
some people feel so very busy waiting !
the one who really might anticipate,
or hardly ever thought about creating.

how many other systems you create !
are never yet designed specifically,
for such an easy way to calculate !
eternal life is only getting risky.
poem2:
human beings having social moneys !
that works for those whose mother earth denies !
a hundred thousand seven donor countries,
to join their daily private enterprise.

too many people under carbon credits,
who had become divided equally !
not any economic benefits,
or human being buried by the needy.

poem1:
and even thus , my soul , be it with thee ,
this easter day .
with loins girt about , and staff in hand ,
as one made ready for the promised land ,
who may not stay ;
poem2:
as free and urgent as the air that moves ,
as quick to tremble as æolian strings ,
the soul responds and thrills to hates and loves ,
desires and hopes , and joys and sufferings ,
and sympathy ’ s soft touch and anger ’ s stings .

( by the light in my shaking hand ) to the like of the masks of stone ;
and with horror i shrieked aloud as i flung my torch and fled ,
and a fire-snake writhed where it fell ; and at midnight
the sky was red .
poem2:
before, or during any other time,
event itself becomes itself. the scene,
itself becomes itself. the story- crime,
itself. the poem. even poem. all.
because. because because because because.
the moment changes, changes over small,
discrete events, because they are the laws.
because events become themselves because.
because because. the story changes) pause.

poem1:
‘ only be still , and in the silence grow , ’
if thou art seeking what the gods bestow .
this is the simple , safe , and certain way
that leads to knowledge for which all men pray
of higher laws to govern things below .
poem2:
last night i watched for death —
so sick of life was i !—
when in the street beneath
i heard his watchman cry
the hour , while passing by .

poem1:
beyond the pearled horizons lie
winter and night : awaiting these
we garner this poor hour of ease ,
until love turn from us and die
beneath the drear november trees .
poem2:
come to the hills , the woods are green —
the heart is high when love is sweet —
there is a brook that flows between
two mossy trees where we can meet ,
where we can meet and speak unseen .

poem1:
the church-bells rock and jangle , and there is peace on the earth .
peace and good will and plenty and christmas games and mirth .
o , the gold glints bright on the wind-vane as it shifts above the
squire 's house ,
and the water of the bar of salcombe is muttering about the bows .
poem2:
this is the story , strange and true ,
that the great captain alau
told to his brother the tartar khan ,
when he rode that day into kambalu
by the road that leadeth to ispahan .

will his strength slay thy worm in hell ? go to :
cover thy countenance , and watch , and fear .

poem1:
for , i through the day , have been guarded by one ,
who , greater and wiser than i ,
has pitied my frailty ; and forced me to shun
illusive temptations , where i might have run
the peril of sporting to die .
poem2:
yonder the long horizon lies , and there by night and day
the old ships draw to home again , the young ships sail away ;
and come i may , but go i must , and if men ask you why ,
you may put the blame on the stars and the sun and the white road
and the sky !

poem1:
that lime tree on the distant rising ground
( if it was a lime tree ) showed her yellow leaves
above the renewed green of wet august grass —
first autumn yellow that on first autumn eves
too soon was found .
poem2:
to outer land of foreign domination !
i see that silver yellow mountain chain !
this tiny little boxing federation,
is lying under boiling water main.

or falling over south america,
its slowly sinking under river drains.
a billion people passing through sahara,
another hundred thousand mountain chains.

poem1:
there without crook or sling ,
walks the good shepherd ; blossoms white and red
round his meek temples cling ;
and to sweet pastures led ,
his own loved flock beneath his eye is fed .
poem2:
to see that nothing could become unwise.
this one is written on the status quo,
but when some people try to compromise !
they might expect an answer even though.

not there no matter whether fully willing,
or having such a very special stance !
so many major brothers from submitting !
we never really had a second chance.

poem1:
i wonder if you ever dream of other days ,
because , sometimes , at twilight when the sunset
plays
half wistfully across the polished oaken floor ,
i see you smiling — standing in your place once more .
poem2:
too many people going on commission.
this little economic policy,
they never wanted any opposition !
he only had a continental army.

i wonder william henry harrison !
is threatened by his very own election,
the nation under thomas jefferson !
no one has risen from a ruling session.

another silly little magazine.
poem2:
it always wants to settle down) until,

exact amounts, until, exhausted still,

until, like women, its demands become,
instead of simply fewer, larger stuff.
because, again, the human body some,
perhaps, of us possesses is designed,
instead of being content to be mind.

poem1:
the sharper , more horrid the pressure , the harder
the heart
that saves the blue grain of eternal fire
within its quick , committed to hold and wait
and suffer unheeding , only forbidden to expire .
poem2:
not o'er thy dust let there be spent
the gush of maudlin sentiment ;
such drift as that is not for thee ,
whose life and deeds and songs agree ,
sublime in their simplicity .

poem1:
weeds of the waste uptossed lie there
on the sandy space that the tide leaves bare ,
ever at ebb some waif or stray
that ever the flood wave washes away ,
and round and round in the lonely bay .
poem2:
the very notion, even in its first,
initial stages of conception call,
perhaps to our advantage, even worst,
upon the poet, as the only man,
upon the artist. therefore i will speak,
although i cannot say another- than,
without the poets, what is music weak,
or music over weak, unless, perhaps,
without the artists even music lapse.
